item.title: Norway's crown princess’ son arrested again for allegedly violating restraining order against ex-girlfriend
item.description: Marius Borg Hoiby, son of Norway’s Crown Princess Mette-Marit, was rearrested for violating a restraining order against his ex-girlfriend after initial detention in August for causing bodily harm to that woman. He now faces additional allegations of domestic abuse and threats against others. Hoiby denied all accusations, according to his lawyer.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: JD Vance explains why he changed his stance for Donald Trump, Elon Musk reacts
item.description: "If you were to ask what caused me to change my tune about President Trump from 2016 to 2020, I could give you a few reasons. But what we're seeing in Springfield really drives it home," Ohio senator JD Vance said. Ohio's Springfield has been on the edge over the bizarre rumor that Haitians immigrants living there have been killing pet cats and dogs to eat them.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: When Laura Loomer said she's single because she's too focused on Donald Trump
item.description: ​"Because Trump is more important than you. Trump is going to save our country. And so you need to understand that President Trump is more important than you. And if you think that you’re more important than President Trump, then you have some kind of, like, delusional personality disorder. I have to say that was the end of that relationship. President Trump’s my number-one priority right now," Laura said earlier explaining why she's single.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: New video claims Africans in Dayton were grilling cats, JD Vance says 'shame on Kamala'
item.description: Amid the major controversy over rumors that Haitians are eating cats and dogs in Ohio's Springfield, a new video posted by Christopher F Rufo, claimed that African migrants last year were filmed grilling cats in Dayton. And the claim found its backing from GOP's vice presidential candidate JD Vance who condemned how the story "debunked" by media turned out to have merit. "Kamala Harris and her media apparatchiks should be ashamed of themselves," Vance said sharing Christopher's post.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'I am not a racist': Woman who started Haitian rumor regrets how 'it just exploded'
item.description: Erika Lee, the woman whose Facebook post became the source of the rumors that Haitian immigrants were eating cats and dogs, said she's not racist and she never thought that her post would gain so much traction landing up at Donald Trump's table. She said she herself is mixed race and a member of the LGBTQ community and her daughter is half-black.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'This plane is going down': California man shouts on plane, threatens to kill everyone
item.description: Charles Angel Salva from California said he assaulted the crew because he did not want anyone to know that he was a pedophile. He said he molested his own child and lost the custody rights. He pulled the chain of the Frontier Airlines because he wanted the plane to crash. He felt that everyone on the flight wanted him to admit to his crime.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Bill Maher versus Laura Loomer over 'arranged relationship' with Trump
item.description: Bill Maher said Laura Loomer looks like she's Donald Trump's type and wondered whether there is any arranged relationship between Donald Trump and Laura Loomer to affect thhe 2024 election. Laura Loomer accused Bill of defaming her and said she should sue Bill Maher for her character assassination campaign. She said she's a private citizen and an investigative journalist but is being targeted by the Democrats.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Abdelmadjid Tebboune secures second term as Algeria's president with 84.3 percent votes
item.description: Abdelmadjid Tebboune secured a second term as Algeria's president with 84.3 percent of the vote, according to final results announced by the Constitutional Court. The election had a turnout of 46.1 percent among over 24 million registered voters. Rival candidates challenged the results, alleging irregularities and fraud in the vote count.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Laura Loomer says she's targeted as she broke the story of Kamala Harris' husband's affair
item.description: That Doug Emhoff's marriage with Kerstin ended because of Doug's extra-marital affair is not unknown. Laura Loomer said she broke the news and hence now she's being targeted for just saying that the White House will smell of curry if Kamala Harris is elected the president. "It's a bit overblow," Laura Loomer said after Donald Trump issued a statement on Laura and strategically exited the controversy.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Former Kuwaiti prime minister Sheikh Jaber Mubarak Al Sabah dies at 82
item.description: Sheikh Jaber Mubarak Al Hamad Al Mubarak Al Sabah, former Prime Minister of Kuwait, passed away at the age of 82. Born in 1942, he held numerous key roles including ministerial positions and served as Prime Minister from November 2011 until his resignation in 2019. He significantly influenced Kuwait's governance during his tenure.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: How Montreal by-polls can deal a blow to faltering support for Canadian PM Justin Trudeau
item.description: Prime Minister Justin Trudeau faces significant pressure as his Liberal Party readies for a crucial by-election in Montreal. Polls indicate a close contest with Bloc Québécois and NDP candidates. Internal party tensions and falling approval ratings compound the challenges. The by-election result could be pivotal for the party's prospects in the upcoming general election.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Could cause embarrassment': Brazilian court rejects baby name citing bullying concerns
item.description: Catarina and Danillo Prímola faced initial rejection from a Brazilian court when they tried to name their newborn Piyé, citing potential bullying risks. After explaining its cultural significance, the court reversed its decision. This case is similar to previous naming disputes in Tennessee and France where courts intervened over concerns of ridicule.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Climate march shuts down Hague motorway during police strike
item.description: Extinction Rebellion climate activists blocked a major motorway running through The Hague on Saturday, their "most disruptive" action yet to protest against billions of euros in Dutch fossil fuel subsidies. Extinction Rebellion (XR) said some protesters planned to take advantage of the police absence to camp out overnight in the motorway tunnels.

item.title: Jailed former Pakistan PM Imran Khan booked for inciting official to mutiny
item.description: Former Pakistan prime minister Imran Khan has been charged with inciting government officers to mutiny and creating chaos. The Federal Investigation Agency is investigating his social media accounts for posts that allegedly undermine national security. This follows a controversial post comparing past and present military leaderships and urging review of a judicial commission report.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Iran successfully launches research satellite, sparks Western concerns
item.description: Iran launched the Chamran-1 research satellite into orbit using a rocket developed by the Revolutionary Guard. The satellite aims to test space hardware and software. This is Iran's second launch this year, raising Western concerns about potential ballistic missile development, which Iran denies. The launch coincides with heightened regional tensions.

item.title: Trump distances himself from Laura Loomer’s racist remarks after backlash: 'I disagree with her statements'
item.description: Donald Trump defended far-right activist Laura Loomer following her racist comments about Kamala Harris, clarifying she does not work for his 2024 campaign but is a supporter. While distancing himself from her statements, he praised her passion and criticized Democratic leaders during his California tour.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: JK Rowling slams Indian-origin trans executive over rape crisis centre failings
item.description: JK Rowling has condemned Mridul Wadhwa, the former CEO of Edinburgh Rape Crisis Centre, after a report revealed significant failures in safeguarding women-only spaces. Wadhwa resigned following an investigation that found she lacked professional standards. The ERCC board has committed to implementing recommendations to enhance their services and protect women-only spaces.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Police fatally shoot man hiding in bathtub in Brooklyn apartment
item.description: Jean Baptiste, 38, was fatally shot by Brooklyn police while serving a bench warrant. He was wanted for three murders and found hiding in a bathtub with a knife. After an ineffective Taser attempt and an alleged attack on an officer, police used deadly force. The incident is under investigation.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk
